  url = {https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S2001037022002264},
  urldate = {2026-02-26},
  abstract = {Single-cell sequencing has gained popularity in recent years. Despite its numerous applications, single-cell DNA sequencing data is highly error-prone due to technical biases arising from uneven sequencing coverage, allelic dropout, and amplification error. With these artifacts, the identification of somatic genomic variants becomes a challenging task, and over the years, several methods have been developed explicitly for this type of data. Single-cell variant callers implement distinct strategies, make different use of the data, and typically result in many discordant calls when applied to real data. Here, we review current approaches for single-cell variant calling, emphasizing single nucleotide variants. We highlight their potential benefits and shortcomings to help users choose a suitable tool for their data at hand.},
